                                </ol>
                                <ul>
                                <li>Before you submit: Steps to take</li>
                                </ul>
                                <ol>
                                <li>After you submit: What to expect</li>
                                <li>Before you write: What we look for</li>
                                </ol>
                                <p>
                                    Length: Pieces articles typically run about 600 to 800 words, though longer is OK. More than 1,000 words, however, usually is not ok.</p>
                                <p>
                                    Topics: Our content educates and motivates and finally markets. At GetValue.co users are looking for articles that inspire, give insight into current trends and offer actionable takeaway tips on the most impactful products and services available at our site store.</p>
                                <p>
                                    Clear and Focused message: We’re looking for new and fresh perspectives on topics our site users care about. To ensure you are offering an original idea:</p>
                                <ul>
                                <li>Search the site. You’ll discover what topics, products or services our site users enjoy and what and how we’ve already written on a topic. Make sure the article you pitch offers something our site users and Insiders haven’t seen before.</li>
                                <li>Consider your personal experience. What problems have you overcome? What unique perspectives can you bring? Telling that story is much more preferable than a personally inexperienced one while relating it to how the product you are promoting from our site store has helped you solve all of your previous problems.</li>
                                <li>Look to the current events. News, events, life and industry changes might spark an article, a promotional material or a product or service review only you can write. Consider if you have insights into how a change might impact current life practices and how business owners and people in general can use a product or a service you are promoting to make them be prepared for such change.</li>
                                </ul>
                                <p>
                                    Step-By-Step Actionable advice: Stories that don’t give our site users some of the actionable advice or takeaways tips from any product or service you are promoting won’t likely be selected for publication. To us, advice means usable, numbered tips our site can put to use right away. This is why tips in articles should be clear enough for our site user to put into action right away. The best tips are often ideas our site users haven’t seen before but offer them a new solution to a common problem.</p>
                                <p>
                                    Trustworthy sources: Be knowledgeable about the sources you cite. Rely on primary sources as much as possible. And remember that, most crowd sources of information from the public sites, doesn’t always offer the most accurate information. In general, we like to see Vendors, Insiders and Contributors to provide in at least a few links to the products they are interested to sell from only our site store. In this sense, while Insiders and Contributors may be allowed to proved links to outside websites (not GetValue.co or their own company) where our site users can find more information or additional resources on the topics discussed, GetValue.co Doesn’t allow Vendors, Insiders and Contributors to provide links linking our site users to products from other sites other than that of Get Value, Inc Companies’ sites.</p>
                                <p>
                                    Help snagging interviews: GetValue.co Insiders are happy to help approved Outsiders and contributors line up interviews with relevant sources. However, please run potential interviewees by your editor and get approval before scheduling an interview on your own, particularly if the person is well-known or notable. It’s possible a GetValue.co Insider may have already reached out to the person, and we want to avoid duplicate coverage.</p>
                                <p>
                                    Please note: While Outsiders and Contributors may say they are working on an article for GetValue.co when they approach public relations professionals or potential sources, other than Insiders, outsiders and contributors “ARE NOT” members of GetValue.co staff and that they should present themselves as independent parties working with GetValue.co and not represent themselves as staffs in such events or in communications with any sources.</p>
                                <ol>
                                <li>Style guidelines: How to write</li>
                                </ol>
                                <ul>
                                <li>No serial commas: apples, oranges and bananas — not apples, oranges, and bananas smileys instead.</li>
                                <li>The dashes we use have double hyphens and spaces: The CEO — whom the board tried to fire — addressed the scandal. We don’t use other kinds of dashes or, heaven forbid, hyphens for dashes.</li>
                                <li>Commas and periods go inside the end quote marks. This should be “ALWAYS”.</li>
                                <li>No double spaces after periods. To repeat again: “NO DOUBLE SPACES AFTER SENTENCES”.</li>
                                <li>Appropriate sourcing of quotes: This means that quotes should be attributed to a source, e.g.: statements like “‘Blah, blah, blah, Gaston Ngailo told me in an interview’ -OR- ‘Blah, blah, blah, Gaston Ngailo said in an interview with the On air With Millard Ayo or New York Times.?’” Are acceptable.</li>
                                <li>Single quotes belong only around quotes within quotes and in headlines and subheads. “NOWHERE ELSE”.</li>
                                <li>When putting affiliate links or any other links to other sites of your own interest, put in your own hyperlinks. Don’t put URLs in parentheses and expect Insiders to link them.</li>
                                <li>While writing articles, use one-sentence paragraphs sparingly. Too many makes your piece clunky. Three to four sentences is an ideal paragraph length.</li>
                                <li>Percent is used as a word. Never use %, except in charts.</li>
                                <li>While designing your head of your article, concentrate of a very short but complete and clear version of it relating to your main articles massage.</li>
                                <li>Subheads (copy that breaks up long chunks of text) should have the same, parallel format.</li>
                                <li>Don’t capitalize the words in subheads, after the first word.</li>
                                <li>If the first head is a full sentence, they all should be. If one has a verb, they all should have a verb.</li>
                                <li>Don’t use links in subheads. As described above, use them only in your text inside your article.</li>
                                <li>It is true that women hold up half the sky. Therefore; if you must use he, also use she don’t hesitate to use them. But always get around this awkward construction of at least sometimes, by pluralizing your pronouns. Instead of “An entrepreneur has his business to do”, make it “Entrepreneurs have their business to do” or instead of using He or she use they.</li>
                                <li>A company or organization or government agency is “an” or “it” and&nbsp; never “a” or “they”. Therefore; for the possessive pronoun, when you refer to possession by a single person or company, use “it’s” not “their”. Similarly, while remembering that, An audience is not “a” or “them”, when you write about a company’s web audience, mention the audience’s members before mentioning the same audience by using “them”.</li>
                                <li>Be consistent: If you start with the pronoun “you”, stick with it. Avoid mixing “we”, “I,” “he/she” and “you” all in the same context and content. Being consistence also mean sticking with the same verb tense throughout. While GetvalueCliks.com accepts other forms of tenses, remember that, the present perfect tense (That person has done the same thing for years) expresses ongoing, habitual action is much more acceptable.</li>
                                <li>Check for repetition of the same words, points and themes. That’s just to help you avoid poor writing.</li>
                                <li>Numbers under 10 are written out (unless appearing with the word percent.) Numbers 10 or higher are written as numerals (unless they start a sentence). Years are always expressed with numerals. Use “more than” rather than “over” with numbers.</li>
                                <li>Check quotes with reliable sources. Brainy quotes and unedited blogs are not reliable and therefore not acceptable.</li>
                                <li>Try to use simple language that everyone can understand and If in any case you must use jargons, particularly abbreviations and acronyms nobody else knows, spell these out on the first reference (followed by the abbreviation in parentheses). If possible avoid Abbreviations altogether. We don’t like that one. And In fact, we hate it.</li>
                                <li>Names: For the first reference, use the full name: Gaston Ngailo. For subsequent references, use the last name only. Even if Gaston Ngailo is your best friend, even if he was the best man at your wedding, don’t call him Gaston in your article.</li>
                                <li>Videos and Photos; If your article includes an embedded video from any video site or you include a photo both they should be from an original source or comes from a free or paid to use or else has no copy rights restrictions. Whenever necessary credits for any un original content from you as an Outsider or a Contributor personally.</li>
                                </ul>
